I checked the implementation of `Files.createDirectories` locally and it does ignore duplicate directories, so it shouldn't throw a `FileAlreadyExistsException`:

```scala
scala> val p = java.nio.file.Paths.get("/tmp/foo")
p: java.nio.file.Path = /tmp/foo
scala> java.nio.file.Files.createDirectories(p)
res2: java.nio.file.Path = /tmp/foo
scala> java.nio.file.Files.createDirectories(p)
res3: java.nio.file.Path = /tmp/foo
```

Here's the code in `java.nio.files.Files` which is used by `createDirectories` and which ignores directories:

```scala
private static void createAndCheckIsDirectory(Path dir,
                                              FileAttribute<?>... attrs)
    throws IOException
{
    try {
        createDirectory(dir, attrs);
    } catch (FileAlreadyExistsException x) {
        if (!isDirectory(dir, LinkOption.NOFOLLOW_LINKS))
            throw x;
    }
}
```

So I'm not sure how we get this exception here!
